Autodesk CFD Tutorial

Human Comfort in Ventilation Systems

Author: Tran Thanh Tung (230079)  |  Software: Autodesk CFD Ultimate  |  Level: Intermediate

Welcome to Autodesk CFD. Computational Fluid Dynamics (CFD) allows engineers to simulate fluid flow and heat transfer. In this tutorial, we will analyze the air quality and thermal comfort inside an exhibit hall.

1. Installation Guide

Before beginning the simulation, ensure the software is correctly installed.

  1. Access: Go to the Autodesk Education portal and log in.
  2. Select Product: Search for Autodesk CFD Ultimate.
  3. Subscription: Select the plan representing your educational role (Student).
  4. Install: Click "Get Product" → "Install" or "Download".
  5. Setup: Run the downloaded setup file and follow the on-screen instructions to complete the installation.

2. Project Overview: Human Comfort

We will simulate a ventilation system in a building to ensure occupants are comfortable during different seasons.

Goals of this Tutorial:
  • Evaluate flow and temperature distributions for "Summer" and "Winter" design days.
  • Assess whether the occupant thermal comfort level is within acceptable bounds.
  • Determine if modifications to the ventilation strategy are necessary.

3. Materials & Geometry Setup

3.1 Importing Geometry

1. Open Autodesk CFD.

2. Click Open (Folder icon) and locate the tutorial file Exhibit Hall.cfz in C:\Users\Public\Public Documents\Autodesk\CFD 2023\Tutorials\Exhibit Hall.

Navigation Tip: Use Shift + Mouse to rotate the view. Scroll to zoom in/out.

3.2 Assigning Materials

You must tell the software what each part is made of. Click on the parts in the model to select them, then click Edit.

Object in Model Material Setting Type
Building Air VolumeAirFluid
FloorBrickSolid
Roof / BenchesWood (Soft)Solid
OccupantsHumanSolid

Note: Ensure you apply the settings after selecting the materials.

4. Boundary Conditions & Meshing

4.1 Boundary Conditions

Define how air and heat enter/exit the system.

  • Supply Air Duct: Select the inlet face. Assign a Volume Flow Rate and Temperature (based on Summer conditions).
  • Return Air Outlet: Select the outlet face. Assign Pressure = 0 (Static Gage).
  • Exterior Walls: Select outer walls. Assign a Film Coefficient (Heat Transfer Coefficient) to simulate heat loss/gain from the outside environment.
  • Occupants: Assign heat generation (metabolic rate) to the human models.

4.2 Meshing

The mesh divides the geometry into small elements for calculation.

  1. Go to the Mesh Sizing tab.
  2. Click Autosize. The software will automatically calculate the optimal mesh distribution.
  3. (Optional) Refine the mesh around the human models for better accuracy.

5. Analysis Case Setup

5.1 Summer Scenario

We will first run the simulation for the Summer condition.

  1. Go to the Solve ribbon.
  2. Result Quantities: Click the "Physics" or "Result quantities" button. Ensure Thermal Comfort is checked.
  3. Iterations: Set the number of iterations (e.g., 100-500) to ensure convergence.

5.2 Winter Scenario (Cloning)

Instead of setting up everything again, we duplicate the work.

  1. Right-click the "Summer" scenario in the Design Study Bar.
  2. Select Clone. Name it "Winter".
  3. Modify the Inlet Temperature and Wall Film Coefficients to reflect cold winter conditions.

5.3 Solver Manager

Use the Solver Manager to queue both simulations. Click Submit to run them sequentially. This may take some time depending on your computer's speed.

6. Results & Conclusion

Once the solver finishes, visual results will appear.

6.1 Visualizing Data

  • Iso Surfaces: Use this to see 3D clouds of temperature zones.
  • Cut Planes: Create a 2D slice through the room to see airflow patterns.

6.2 Evaluating Thermal Comfort

Look for the Predicted Mean Vote (PMV) result. This is a standard scale for human comfort:

  • +3: Hot
  • 0: Neutral (Comfortable)
  • -3: Cold

Compare the Summer vs. Winter results. If the PMV around the occupants is near 0, the ventilation strategy is successful.
